# API Rules - Blocking a specific field-change. · pocketbase pocketbase · Discussion #4208
created: 2024-01-22, last updated: 2026-04-16, [Read more](https://github.com/pocketbase/pocketbase/discussions/4208)

You can use the `:isset` field modifier.
For example:
```
// either no role submitted or the submitted role matches with the existing value (aka. no change)
(@request.data.role:isset = false || role = @request.data.role)
```
...
For example:
```
// either no role submitted or the submitted role matches with the existing value (aka. no change)
(@request.data.role:isset = false || role = @request.data.role)
```
...
Another solution could be to intercept onRecordBeforeUpdateRequest.
```
onRecordBeforeUpdateRequest((e) => {
try {
const requestInfo = $apis.requestInfo(e.httpContext);
if (requestInfo.authRecord !== null) {
e.record.set("role", "hardCodedRole");
}
} catch (e) {
console.error(e);
}
}, "collection_name");
```
The above example will always set collection_name.role to 'hardCodedRole'.
You should put additional logic in there to determine the hardCodedRole based on your conditions.
Like pulling in the previous record with `e.record.originalCopy()` and `.get('role')`.

# How to use the API Rules? · pocketbase pocketbase · Discussion #1157
created: 2022-12-01, last updated: 2026-04-17, [Read more](https://github.com/pocketbase/pocketbase/discussions/1157)

The rule `@request.auth.id = poster.id` translates to: "Allow only authenticated user with id matching the poster.id to perform this operation".
So this means that you need to be authenticated before sending the delete request (eg. `pb.collection('users').authWithPassword('test@example.com', '123456')`).
...
@JatinjayJAM The id of the current record must be equal to the current authenticated user id (this rule usually makes sense when used in auth collections).
...
@JatinjayJAM It is hard to say because it depends on your collections structure and what are the desired constraints you want to enforce, but if we assume that there is a `comments` collection with a "user" non-empty single `relation` field, then an example `comments` rules set could be:
...
// update - roughly translates to:
// allow changes of the record only if the current user field matches the auth.id
// AND
// don't allow users to change the comment's user value to another user id (aka. they can submit only the same user id or none)
user = @request.auth.id &&
(@request.data.user = @request.auth.id || @request.data.user:isset = false)
```

